ce:section.ce:para:
Disassembling the battery to obtain various component materials and measuring the thickness of their single layers. According to the thickness measurement of the components in various SOH (Summarized in Table 1
                        ), the thickness change of the anode is the main reason for the increase of the battery thickness. The thickness of the cathode and separator did not change significantly with battery aging, while the anode became thicker, which may be related to the growth of the SEI layer and lithium plating reaction on the anode surface. Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) was used to observe the surface morphology of battery components on the micro scale. In order to avoid the reaction with substances in the air which influences the surface morphology of components, the samples were disassembled in the glove box and made into SEM samples, which were only exposed to the environment during the transfer from the sealed container to the SEM vacuum chamber. There were microscopic visual differences between the aged batteries and fresh batteries when viewed under SEM (Figure 2
                        ). As the battery ages, it can be observed that the surface of graphite particles is covered by SEI layers, which corresponds to the increase in negative electrode thickness with battery aging. The thicknesses of the SEI layers on the anodes of batteries with SOH values of 1, 0.88, and 0.82 were measured using the X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) etching method, yielding respective thicknesses of 23 nm, 50.6 nm, and 57.5 nm. Although the porosity of the separator decreases and the surface morphology changes, the thickness changes little for these reasons. There are no clear visual differences between the cathodes.
